segments.text: It was just a department of business then, wasn't it?
It was agricultural economics.
And they were in the building toward the system building from Cushing.
I don't remember.
I really don't.
I'm sorry.
Was Ty Timm there in Ag Econ yet?
Tyris Tim.
Yeah, I don't remember.
I don't think so.
I never heard the name.
As you look back now, what were some of the most important courses that you took?
Well, statistics, business cycles, accounting, of course.
Do you remember who taught that?
No, I don't.
And about the typical business class had how many students in it?
Well, not too many.
That's what I liked.
You know, maybe 20, 30.
And if you needed to see a teacher, one of your instructors, were they hard to locate?
You know, I don't remember having to.
So I can't really answer it.
But I think they used to hang around a while and talk, unless they had another class or something.
I never saw them being aloof or not wanting to talk to somebody.
They all seemed real, real nice.
Do you remember any easy pushover courses?
My freshman year, you know, Spanish.
I spoke Spanish better than the professor did.
Math was real easy then.
My whole freshman year was kind of a pushover.
In fact, had you been well prepared at El Paso High?
For all these things, I was, yes.
Yes, I sure was.
And your problem in chemistry was you hadn't taken chemistry.
I hadn't prepared myself for engineering.
I said, I want to be an engineer.
My parents were immigrants, and they didn't know how to prepare me.
They didn't ask me about the future.
They didn't ask me what I wanted to do.
They just wanted me to go to college.
I thought, you just went to college, you know?
Of course, as I look back, I wouldn't have changed a thing.
I'm really happy with my life, you know.
I'm happy, extra happy with my experience at A&M.
I think it matured me, you know, and I needed that.
Really bad for...
The easy courses, there weren't any special courses for athletes or rich kids or anything like that, were there?
Not that I'm aware of.
I've never heard of it.
I know there was a special table for athletes.
They had better, well I can't say better food.
Maybe they had more food than we did, because the food was good.
Were there any, in your years there, were there any celebrity students?
That is, students that were famous because of their parents being rich or they were great athletes?
No, no, never.
Well, you know, some of the football players we admired, but they didn't.
Who were some of those?
Oh, gosh, let's see.
What was his name?
I thought he was so good-looking, man.
He was really handsome.
He was...
I guess one of his relatives was a senator or a congressman or something.
What was his name?
Not Zabriskie, that was a coach.
Oh, gosh.
Well, besides my cousin Art, you know.
Did any famous people come to visit the campus?
Bob Hope came once.
Really?
Yeah.
Did you see him?
Oh, yeah.
We sat next to him at, what was the name of that restaurant there?
It's probably still there.
Not Hotard's, that was in Bryan.
Is it still there?
No, but it was there when I got there.
Oh man, that was wonderful food for a cafeteria.
And where did Bob Hope perform?
In the hall.
In Bryan Hall.
In Bryan Hall?
And you went to?
Yeah.
And then we went to eat at North Gate restaurant, and he was there eating.
And we sat real close to him there.
But, of course, I didn't ask him for his autograph or anything.
I was still, you know.
And when you and your buddies went to a movie in Guyon Hall, what was it like?
How did Aggies behave at Guyon?
Good.
Did they make noise, though?
No.
Only in reaction to the movie, I think.
Later, apparently, the kids would make lots of noise.
They would shout and ha-ha and boo and so forth.
Wow.
I don't remember.
As you got settled in, where did you and your buddies go to have a good time on Saturday night?
Well, we used to go to the Baptist Church on Wednesday nights.
They had a couple of people there that were real good.
I used to go with a fellow from, I think, Harlingen, right around there.
Name was Frog Nash.
Big old guy.
Just as sweet and lovable as you can imagine.
We used to go together on Wednesday nights.
And I used to love to go with him because...

i can't carry a tune and my voice is terrible but it's not strong he couldn't carry a tune either but he had a big voice and he'd sing so i could sing right along with him because i knew nobody was going to hear me and it was a lot of fun saturdays what was one of the reason for y'all going on wednesday night did they serve food no oh this one no okay and they took a collection but it was just just not it was something to do really we uh
Now, had you been a churchgoer at home?
No.
We grew up Orthodox, so we didn't have a church.
I'm Presbyterian now, but then we didn't have a church.
But when you were in college at A&M, did you go on Sundays?
No, just Wednesday nights.
What did you and your buddies do then on a Sunday?
Well, like on a Saturday, there was a restaurant.
in Bryan, around Bryan somewhere, called Wimpy's.
And they had real steaks that were cheap.
I don't know, a dollar or two dollars, I don't know.
Real thin, and they were pan fried, but they were really good.
And we'd go over there and have a steak, or we'd go to Hotard's and eat, go to a movie.
We didn't drink a lot, so we didn't go out and drink.
How did you get around?
Did you ride the bus much?
We rode the bus, yeah, to Bryan.
And you always wore your uniforms off campus?
Yes, yes.
I always did, except when we turned non-reg my senior year, I didn't.
In fact, I stayed in the Corps one year.
My junior year, one semester,
without a contract.
I just stayed in the Corps.
And then I went non-reg, I figured it wouldn't, you know.
Back to other celebrity visitors other than Bob Hope.
Anybody, any other famous people come?
There was a preacher from Oklahoma that used to come.
Just inspiring and I forgot it.
I think it was Alexander.
I'm not sure used to come from Oklahoma and Give sermons or perform.
I don't know he gave sermons, but he just did him so It was entertainment.
You know, it was so good.
Where did he speak that guy had gone?
Mm-hmm.
Yeah Well now did any of the big orchestras come to play for the dances I
Tommy Dorsey?
You know, probably.
But I only went to one dance, that was my senior ring dance.
That's the only dance I went to.
So I wasn't really aware of it.
The YMCA, is that where you all went to get a soft drink and coffee?
No, we went to Lupo's.
Lupo's Trading Post, I think was the name of it, wasn't it?
Mm-hmm.
Yeah.
Still there at Northgate.
It is?
His son's running it.
Isn't that something?
Where did you buy your books, from Lupo?
I think so.
Did you ever borrow any money from him?
No, never did.
He loaned money to lots of students interest-free to pay for your books.
Wow.
I think, I don't know whether I cashed checks there or some, I think I cashed checks there.
And the post office was at Northgate?
Yeah, yeah, it was close by, yeah.
You didn't have any blind dates with girls from T.W.
Tessie's?
Yeah, Texas, yeah.
I think my junior year.

my cousin's sister fixed us up with a couple of girls and It was a disaster They we hadn't met him we didn't know him and I Guess they looked at us the way we looked at them, you know, it just didn't go and that was the only blind date ever But how were how were young women treated?
on the A&M campus
I thought real good.
I mean, you know, I never heard anybody complain.
I've never heard anything but positive.
Yeah, oh yeah, real good.
You didn't get sick, you didn't have to go to the quack shack?
No, no, never did.
Is that what they called it?
In general, describe the student body when you were there.
Where were they from?
What kind of families?
Where geographically?
What were their attitudes?
Gosh, they were from all over the state.
We had a few from Mexico, too.
I don't know.
They all had really good attitudes.
Everybody that I met did.
Were they rich boys, poor boys?
You never could tell.
You never could tell whether they had money or not.
Everybody was treated the same.
Nobody asked if they had money.
I couldn't tell.
That's one of the common threads that goes through all these interviews.
Yeah, I really couldn't tell.
And I don't think anybody could tell about me, and I was frugal.
But I don't think anybody ever asked me.
I don't think anybody ever said I was a poor boy.
No, it was real nice.
Now, what did it take to be accepted as one of the group?
I don't know.
I think it just happened.
Am I correct that you had to participate?
Oh, yeah, sure, sure.
But once you did that, you know, you were...
It was kind of like a family.
I mean, you know, all the outfits had cohesion, you know.
They were proud of their outfit and they stuck together.
And there were some Jewish boys and Catholic boys?
Oh yeah, I had two or three.
Yeah, I had two or three Jewish boys in my outfit.
Do you remember what any of those other guys' nicknames were?
No.
Because the Maltz boys from Houston, Jewish.
Oh, yeah, I knew one of them.
Class of 51.
They said their nickname was Jew Boy.
Really?
And I said, was it a put-down?
He said, no, we were proud to be Jewish.
That's right.
No, they never, of course, all the Jewish guys in my outfit were above me.
Mr. Holstey from Galveston, what a cutie.
He was funny.
He was a nice guy, too.
He was an upperclassman.
Bushman, there was one named Bushman.
He was real nice, kind of, he was kind of an upperclassman, you know what I mean?
Where Holst, he was, you know, he was an upperclassman, but he kind of, you know, joked around and kind of, who else?
And did many Aggies have cars then?
No, no, very few.
Now, what year was it that there were so many freshmen with the veterans that they moved the fresh out to the old air base?
That must have been after I left.
Is that right?
I think so, because I don't remember it happening.
Okay, because somewhere about that time, and so the sophomores didn't have anybody to haze.
Oh, boy.
No, no, that didn't happen while I was there.
I graduated in June of 49.
I believe maybe it's that fall.
Describe the religious activities on campus and around the campus.
Well, like I said, on Wednesday nights, I used to go to the Baptist Wednesday night meetings.
But there were a number of other congregations.
Yeah, there was an Episcopal congregation.
I went there a couple of times because when we were children, we went to the Episcopal Church because it was the closest in theology and everything to the Orthodox Church.
We went there just a couple of times.
And then that preacher that used to come from Oklahoma,

uh he always drew a crowd it was was there a spring religious emphasis week then there would be in the 50s yeah i don't remember it unless that was what was that was when that guy from oklahoma came down you know that could have been um football games what about basketball games did y'all you and your buddies go to the games i didn't go to many we went to some baseball games
We were freshmen because they used to make us shoot a back gun.
I hated it.
They made us do it, you know.
At the game?
Yeah, at the game, yeah.
So I went to a few games then, but after that I didn't go to many.
Who was the commandant of the Corps when you were there?
Do you remember?
General or colonel?
Yeah.
Was Boatner there yet?
No.
No.
And, you know, Tom Parsons was the commandant there several years ago.
He was in our class.
That's what I thought.
Yeah.
And he was in B battery, I think, when I was in E battery or A battery.
He was a sophomore when I was a freshman.
I've interviewed him.
Nice guy.
Who was the president?
Gilchrist?
Yeah, we had kind of a revolution or something.
They wanted to get rid of
one of the presidents, and we all marched on his home.
The guy, the upperclassmen turned in their sabers.
I don't even remember who it was.
I think it was Gilchrist.
I think it was, yeah.
Were you in that group?
Yes, yeah.
I marched with them, but, you know.
You didn't turn in your saber.
I didn't have one.
We just were supposed to go and we went, you know, yeah.
And as I understand it, he was pretty firm.
He must have been because nothing happened, you know.
Yes.
Was Reveley around?
Yeah, yeah.
What did you and your buddies think of Reveley?
Everybody loved her, you know, she wasn't she wasn't a pest.
Oh, I never saw her except at football games, you know, yeah In fact, I don't know where they kept her or anything What did you and your buddies think about?
Yale leaders and Corps commanders and We thought it was a nice place to be I did you know I thought they deserved it and I think they earned it I mean it was it was something that
You respected them?
Yeah, absolutely, yeah.
It was something that you earned, something you probably worked for, and something you deserved, you know.
Oh, yeah.
As you think back, did you have a favorite Aggie yell?
Saw.
Saw Varsity's horns off?
Saw Varsity's horns off.
Now, you're there between World War II and the Korean War.
So it is a period of boom.
Was the area around the college growing?
It might have been just beginning to.
It wasn't boom boom yet, you know.

but college view those married student apartments for the veterans was crowded yeah oh yeah what kind of students how what quality of students were the veterans they were a lot better students than they would have been out of high school they were really serious about their education i noticed that they had matured they had matured and they were ready you know they they really i got to know several of them and everything and they really
Had a mission.
I mean, they wanted an education, and they were going to get it, and they were going to learn, and they worked at it.
All the ones I knew.
Did you non-veterans think that they made it tougher for you all to make good grades?
I didn't.
I didn't.
No, but, you know, they might have made us study a little harder just because we saw how they were doing and how they appreciated education and valued it.
Now, there were also some veterans living in temporary housing down near Kyle Field, weren't there?
I don't remember those.
What did you and your buddies think about the band?
Oh, we lived with the band.
They were above us, you know.
And we knew them as individuals, as people, and they were wonderful.
And they worked hard.
Did they?
They worked hard.
You know, they used to practice every afternoon.
They gave up a lot of their time, and it showed.
Did you and your buddies ever play tricks on them?
Did the, was there in the dormitory any?
No, no, I don't remember doing anything with them.
I think when we were with B Battery, we used to have those, what did they used to call them when we used to flood a guy out?
Drownouts.
Drownouts, yeah, we had a couple of those, not many.
But no, I don't think, I never did.
Do you remember any good stories about pranks, Good Bull?
Any tricks that you may have known about?
Did you ever go down in the steam tunnels?
No.
Really?
Never did.
Never even knew there were steam tunnels.
Nobody ever told me.
Did you know that there were secret fraternities?
No, I didn't.
Were there?
Were very many people aware of that?
No.
That's what I thought.
Very, very few.
Let's see, we did hitchhiking and dates.
When you and your buddies went out to have a good time on Saturday night, you sometimes went out to eat, went to a movie.
Where did people go to have a drink?
You know, I don't know.
I never went.
I really don't know.
Did you not drink any beer, any whiskey in those years?

One time, my senior year, or was it my junior year, in the non-regs, I had broken up with my wife that I had met previously at TSCW, and she was coming down to a dance with one of her boyfriends that she knew from her hometown.
And I wanted to sneak a peek at her, see if I could see her, find her, and my roommate, Ken Hone,
got a bottle of wine.
I don't know where he got it from.
And I did get drunk and I never went out.
I got drunk and conked out.
And that was the only time I remember that I had a drink.
Where were you when you did that drink?
In my room.
Oh, in your room?
Yeah.
Okay.
And so it wasn't with a big crowd or anything?
No, no.
I never, and I don't even know whether, I don't think I even drank on court trips.
All right.
Did any of your buddies ever go to Uncle Ed's, to Hard Liquor's?
I don't even remember.
I don't even know Uncle Ed's.
That was down the Welborn Road, directly south of Kyle Field, about a mile.
Isn't that something?
Then Whiskey Bridge.
That was straight west going to Snook.
You went into the next county where alcohol was legal.
I must have run around with a lot of teetotalers because I never remember those.
I mean, I didn't even know about those things.
I wasn't aware of it.
Let's see.
What were Aggies smoking then?
Cigarettes.
What kind?
Yeah.
What brands?
Mostly non-filters.
I know I smoked Camels.
I smoked for 10 years.
Mm-hmm.
I started at A&M.
You started at A&M?
I started at A&M.
Looking back, what percentage do you suspect of Aggies smoked?
Did you know some Aggies that rolled their own?
I never saw one.
What about cigars?

few pipes maybe a couple i saw yeah mostly cigarettes and did you all know that drugs existed had you ever heard the word marijuana or heroin i might have heard it but i never was aware of i don't think i heard it at a m the only time i ever heard about drugs
was one of the drivers that used to bring stuff to my dad's store said something about marijuana one time.
I didn't even know what it was, but I never did hear about it at A&M.
I wasn't aware of drugs at all.
I don't think it was a big thing then, but it might have been.
I mean, you know, I don't know.
If you needed advice, who did you turn to?
Well, I used to go to my cousin Arthur, you know, when he was there.
And he was real good.
And then, of course, Albert Mullooly was there, too, and I'd go see him.
Now, Al Mullooly is what year ahead of you?
He was a class of 45.
Forty-five.
Okay.
All right.
And I'd go see him.
Was there an El Paso hometown club?
I might have gone to a meeting once.
I don't know.
I remember the football player's name now.
Monty Moncrief.
Oh, yes.
Oh, yes.
Good-looking guy.
Yes, yes, yes.
Good football player, too.
Now, you came home every summer.
Yes.
And did you work for the family every summer?
Except that first summer.
All right.
As you go back your third year, you didn't get a contract.
No.
Do you have any idea why?
I think flat feet or something.
Because during the Korean War I got called.
And this was right after my wedding.
I got married September 3rd.
I had to go for my physical September the 11th.
So we went to New Orleans, came back for our honeymoon, came back to El Paso.
And went and got my physical, and didn't pass that either.
And I think it was my flat feet.
That's the only thing I could think of.
You know, physically I was in good shape, but I never... Now, where did you meet this special young lady?
I met her at TSCW.
Okay.
She was Lebanese.
From where?
From Marshall, Texas.
Marshall.
And how long had her family been in the United States?
A long time, a lot longer than we had.
In fact, she didn't even speak Arabic.
I mean, her parents spoke Arabic to keep secrets from the children.
It had reached that stage.
And so you meet her while you're at A&M?
I met her on a court trip.
One of my cousins introduced me.
That was it.
Introduced me, hi, hi, and that was it.
I forgot about her.
You know, that was all.
Then we went, I had two cousins that were at TSCW.
We went up there for a weekend four or five months later.
She introduced me again.
And God, this time I thought, gosh, she's so beautiful.
She's so nice.
I don't know what happened the first time that I didn't.
When you went up there, you and your buddies, where did you all stay in Denton?
We stayed in a motel.
Oh, did you?
Yeah.
And a bunch of you piled into one car to go up there?
Well, usually just my cousin and I would go.
And sometimes we'd take, I think there was a fellow named Dave Goddard that was in our junior or senior year that was going with Abe's sister, and he'd go up with us.
All right, now as this romance builds, how did y'all communicate?
We wrote.
Yeah, letters.
You didn't get on the phone very often, I bet.
No.
And she still got some of the letters.
Oh, good.
I had a bunch.
I don't know what happened.
Oh, good, good, good.
Now, pass those on to the children so they stay in the family.
Don't let those get thrown away.
And as you're looking toward graduation, what did you think you were going to do
when you graduated from A&M?
Well, I interviewed.
And, you know, I was still a bashful, backward kind of guy, and I interviewed with J.C. Penney, I think, or Sears, one of those, and I just, you know, didn't know how to talk to him.
And, of course, we'll let you know.
Didn't even get a letter from him.
I came home, and I said, well, I didn't know what I was going to do.
I just...
Didn't have much self-confidence and just said, well, I don't know.
I came home and got a job with a truck line, minimum wage, keeping books.
And I said, well, this isn't for me.
I just can't do this all my life.
I had my girlfriend, you know, and we were kind of getting serious.
So I went to my dad and I says, no, I didn't.
No, I was still working.
for this outfit.
I worked for maybe six months.
And then of course, then we got married.
My wife and I got married September 3rd.
Then I had my physical.
Then I started selling insurance.
And that didn't work.
It was just, it was this dollar a week insurance, you know, with American National.
I stayed with them a year and a half or two.
I said, you know, this just isn't for me.
Joy's father had given her $5,000 as a dowry.
I had $3,000 or $4,000 that I had saved.
I bought a car with, so I didn't have any money.
So I says, you know, Joy, I don't know what to do.
She says, well, why don't we...
Your dad's getting old.
Why don't we buy him out and see?
So we went to Daddy, and I says, Daddy...
Why don't I take over here?
He said, well, let's take inventory and see how much it is.
Anyway, it ended up being $3,600.
So we paid him and we took it over.
And then we started from there.
And then things got better.
Business picked up.
Let's see, we did this in, I don't know, 51 or 52.
Business got so good, we tore the house down, built the store behind it about three times as big, then tore the front store down, had a nice little superette, you know, 54.
And so we kept working, business got better, business got better, business got better.
So 58, I bought the house next door.
We tore it down, added to the store.
And by the time we finished, we had a 10,000 square foot grocery store.
We were doing about $3 million a year.
And that's what we did for 30 years.
Then in 1980, we sold the store.
We kept the property.
We sold the store.
And I sold real estate for a couple of years.
My son had this music business that he had started from the store we had set him up in, because that's what he wanted to do.
And he was having a hard time.
by himself, and he'd done a couple of bad deals.
He was about to go bankrupt, and I wanted to get out of the real estate business.
I didn't like it.
I said, maybe I'll go help him.
So I got with him and got him straightened out, and I'm still there.
We've jumped a little, but as you got into the real world of business,
What had you learned at Texas A&M about the real world and about people that helped you?
Everything.
Everything.
I remember just thinking, gosh, you know, if it wasn't for A&M, I wouldn't know this, or I wouldn't have done this.
It just helped me a lot with my judgment.
It helped me a lot with my risk-taking.
And it helped me a lot dealing with people, you know, looking them in the eye, shaking hands with them firmly.
You know, it transformed me.
Really, it did.
